         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" source="#ala2004">
            <p>i. <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/> The fortune of the emperor triumphs! The fortune of the empress triumphs! Many years for the new Theodosius!</p>
            <p>ii. <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/> Many years <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>! Son of God, grant him life! The faith of the Christians triumphs!</p>
            <p>iii. <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
               <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">this work was done</supplied> under <orig>O</orig>
               <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>, <foreign xml:lang="la">pater</foreign>, in the <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/> indiction 
               <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            
            <p>I agree with the suggestion by Benet Salway that i.line 1 did not include letters (as shown in my previous editions), but the traces of decoration, probably the 'bow' at the top of the wreath; 
               see <bibl><ptr target="roueche2007"/> <citedRange>p. 184, and note 9</citedRange></bibl>.</p><!-- check -->
            <p>SEE SEG 60.1077 ALA no. 61. D.Feissel, in Mélanges Cécile Morrisson (= TMByz 16, 2010) 265, suggests restoring in no. 61 III LL. 3/4 ἰνδ(ικτίωνος) [δευ|τέ]ρας (ALA: ἰνδ(ικτιόνι) [. .|. . . .]ΡΑΣ). 
            A second indiction beginning on Sept. 1, 583 A.D. is perfectly compatible with the date of birth of the first son of Μαυρίκιος and Κωνσταντίνη (August 4, 583 A.D.). 
            Ceremonies in honor of the newborn νέ(ος) Θεοδόσιος (no. 61 I LL. 5/6) began in Aphroidisias in Sept. 583 A.D. at the earliest. According to ALA, 
            it is the emperor Anastasius who was acclaimed as ‘new Theodosius’.</p>
         </div>
